 If you're new to web accessi= bility here's a high level guide of some stuff you should know ab= out <= span><= /span>

The Quality Assurance tea= m at Vidyard is committed to creating an accessible application by removing= barriers for people with disabilities.

Below are important tools= /docs used by the QA team.

Accessibility Testing Checklist

For an expanded checklist= with instructions and explanations, see Access= ibility Testing

  • Regular testing
  • UX testing
  • WAVE toolbar
    • Error/alert/feature report
    • Contrast report
    • No styles mode
  • Colour blindness simulator (eg. color = oracle)
  • Windows high contrast mode
  • 200x browser zoom
  • Keyboard navigation
  • Mobile devices
  • Mobile screen readers
    • iOS
    • Windows surface tablet mode

    • JAWS

Tools

Accessibility checkers

WAVE toolbar: Flags errors and poten= tial accessibility issues. Is a good first pass, and makes a good starting = place for learning about web accessibility because it is comprehensive and = explains why issues are problematic and how to fix them. See the expanded a= ccessibility testing checklist for greater detail on how to best use this t= ool.
Google Chrome Accessibility audit tools: can be found in the dev to= ols of chrome. This accessibility checker is faster, lighter weight and eas= ier to use, but has less features and is not as good for helping you to lea= rn about accessibility.

Colour Blindness Simulat= ors

Color Oracle: A colour-blindness = simulator. Shows approximately what the screen will look like to a colour-b= lind user.
Sim Dal= tonism: A better colour-blindness simulator for Mac or iOS only.

Contrast Checkers

Contrast Ratio Checker: This is the contras= t checker I use because it provides a good visual display of the colours us= ed and takes transparency on a variable background into account.
Google = contrast checking: You can now do a quick check of colour contrast in c= hrome's dev tools.

Screen Readers

There's a huge variety of screen reader/browser/OS combinations that use= rs can use. Here's the results from = a 2017 survey of screen reader users and what they most commonly use.=  

For Windows

  • NVDA - NVDA (Nonvisual Desktop Access) is a free Screen Reader. Most commonly u= sed with firefox.
  • Narrator - Comes with OS, but has no text output of screenreader voice.= Narrator is also compatible with tablet mode on the windows surface.
    • caps lock + left and right arrow keys: quick navigation through the pag= e
    • caps lock + up and down arrow keys: change the granularity of quick nav= igation
  • JAWS - don't bother installing this on you computer if you don't = need to. It is installed on the Windows surface. Most commonly used with IE=

For Mac

Voiceover - Comes with MacOS, and iOS. Here = are some useful commands:

  • Cmd + F5 : toggle voiceover on/off
  • Ctrl + option + u : opens rotor with lists of different element type. g= o between lists with left and right arrow keys. You can start searching for= elements in the rotor by typing.
  • ctrl + alt + shift + up/down: frame switching
  • left arrow + right arrow: toggle quick nav. This allows you to move bet= ween all elements using the arrow keys. You will still need a different sho= rtcut to move between frames.

see https://dequeuniversity.com/screenreaders/survi= val-guide for a more comprehensive screenreader shortcut survival guide= .

Resources

Wuhcag: a high level overview of each of the WCAG criteria and wh= at they actually mean, written in easily-understood language.

WCAG Understanding Success Criteria: a more in = depth document with definitions, examples and more technical explanations o= f the WCAG criteria.

Web Accessibility Chec= klist: covers a list of things to to do make the page accessible from a= development perspective, rather than a testing perspective.

WebAIM: W3= is the standards body and has more iso-type documents, if you're looking f= or guidelines or suggestions for a certain type of element, like 'How do I = make a carousel/login form more accessible?', 'How do I write alt text for = a specific type of element?', or 'How do most people use a screen reader?' = you'll want to search WebAIM's website- they're a non-profit that provides = a variety of helpful information.

Writing alt text: one of my most used resources in webAIM is this = article with a list of examples of how to write appropriately descriptive a= lt text.

ARIA Techniques: an outl= ine of how and when to use most of the aria roles that is a good b= alance between technical and readable.

Accessibility lunch and learn and Accessibility onboarding slides for presentations that act a= s an introduction to web accessibility. The lunch and learn is a bit more t= echnical, and the onboarding is a bit more focused on the market.

Deque University: Deque is an accessibility techn= ology and consulting company. If you're looking to delve deeper into a spec= ific topic they offer a variety of courses. Use that professional developme= nt!

Power M= apper: A compatibility matrix of screen reader/browser combinations and= html elements. This is especially useful if you think you're running into = compatibility issues and want to see if there's a known issue. Matrices als= o exist on this site for HTML attributes, ARIA elements, WCAG best practice= s, and an overall look at screen reader reliability.

W3 ARIA authoring pr= actices: instructions with examples for building different types of com= ponents/widgets. Helps you to follow the WCAG guidelines but laid out in a = way that is easier to build from than the WCAG criteria. If you are= a developer building a new component, this may be a very useful resource f= or you.
